Predicting Candidate Attendance in Interviews

ABOUT DATASET

The dataset comprises details of over 1000 candidates and their interview experiences throughout the period from 2014 to 2016

Attribute Information:¶

  1. Date of Interview:

    • The scheduled day for the candidate's interview. Formats may vary.

  2. Client Name:

    • The client who provided the recruitment mandate to the vendor.

  3. Industry:

    • The vertical or industry to which the client belongs. Candidates may explore different industries during their job search.

  4. Location:

    • The current location of the candidate.

  5. Position to be Closed:

    • "Niche" refers to rare skill sets, while "routine" refers to more common skill sets.

  6. Nature of Skillset:

    • The specific skill set that the client is looking for.

  7. Interview Type:

    • Three types of interviews - Walkin drives, Scheduled interviews, and Scheduled Walkins. Each has unique characteristics.

  8. Name (Cand ID):

    • A substitute to keep the candidate's identity confidential.

  9. Gender:

    • Indicates whether the candidate is male or female.

  10. Candidate Current Location:

    • The current location of the candidate.

  11. Candidate Job Location:

    • The expected job location for the candidate.

  12. Interview Venue:

    • The location where the interview is conducted.

  13. Candidate Native Location:

    • The candidate's place of origin.

  14. Permission to Start:

    • Whether the candidate has obtained the necessary permission to start at the required time.

  15. No Unscheduled Meetings:

    • Whether the candidate anticipates any unscheduled meetings.

  16. Three-Hour Call Permission:

    • Can the interviewer call the candidate three hours before the interview for attendance follow-up.

  17. Alternative Number/Desk Number:

    • Can the interviewer contact the candidate using an alternative number or desk number.

  18. Updated Resume and JD Understanding:

    • Whether the candidate has a printout of the updated resume and has read and understood the job description (JD).

  19. Venue Details and Landmark Clarity:

    • Whether the candidate is clear about the interview venue details and landmarks.

  20. Call Letter Sharing:

    • Whether the call letter for the interview has been shared with the candidate.

  21. Expected Attendance:

    • Whether the candidate was expected to attend the interview (Yes, No, or Uncertain).

  22. Observed Attendance:

    • Binary variable indicating whether the candidate attended the interview. This is the dependent variable.

  23. Marital Status:

    • Indicates whether the candidate is married or single.

def rename_expected_attendance(data):
    if pd.isnull(data):
        return np.nan
    attendance=data.rstrip().lower()
    if attendance =='no' or attendance == 'uncertain':
        return attendance
    else:
        return 'yes'
    
df.expected_attendance=df.expected_attendance.apply(rename_expected_attendance)

# Function to map job skills to 'skilled' or 'routine'
def map_job_skills(skill):
    if skill in ['production- sterile', 'selenium testing', 'dot net', 'aml', 'trade finance']:
        return 'skilled'
    elif skill == 'routine':
        return 'routine'
    else:
        return 'unknown'

# Apply the function to 'job_skills_required' column
df['job_skills_required'] = df['job_skills_required'].map(map_job_skills)

# Function to map candidate skills to categories
def map_candidate_skills(skill):
    if pd.isna(skill):  # Check for NaN values
        return 'unknown'
    elif skill in ['routine', 'fresher', 'production']:
        return 'routine'
    elif skill in ['oracle', 'banking operations', 'aml/kyc/cdd', 'cdd kyc', 'biosimiliars', 'ra label', 'ra publishing', 'emea', 'lcm -manager', 'licensing – ra', 'generic drugs – ra', 'biosimilars', 'regulatory', 'analytical r & d', 'analytical r&d', 'senior software engineer-mednet', 'tech lead-mednet', 'tech lead- mednet', 'technical lead', 'sr automation testing', 'tl', 'senior analyst', 'core java', 'java j2ee', 'oracle plsql', 'java,sql', 'automation testing java', 'submission management', 'biosimillar', 'publishing', 'global labelling', 'als testing', 'java developer', 'lending and liabilities', 'lending & liability', 'l & l', 'lending&liablities', 'java/j2ee/struts/hibernate', 'java/spring/hibernate/jsf', 'java', 'java jsf', 'java,j2ee, jsf', 'java ,j2ee', 'java, j2ee', 'java,j2ee', 'java/j2ee/core java', 'java/j2ee', 't-24 developer', 'cots developer', 'product control', 'dot net', 'cots', 'testing', '- sapbo, informatica', 'etl', 'java-sas', 'java tech lead', 'manager', 'java, sql', 'hadoop', 'sccm', 'sccm-(network, sharepoint,ms exchange)', 'sccm- desktop support', 'sccm- networking', 'sccm – sql', 'sccm – sharepoint', 'production support - sccm', 'sas', 'basesas program/ reporting', 'java, spring, hibernate', 'java,spring,hibernate', 'java, xml, struts, hibernate']:
        return 'skilled'
    else:
        return 'unknown'

# Apply the mapping function to 'candidate_skills' column
df['candidate_skills'] = df['candidate_skills'].map(map_candidate_skills)

# Define a function to map each location to its corresponding region
def map_to_region(location):
    south_region = ['hosur', 'trichy', 'chennai', 'cochin', 'trivandrum', 'coimbatore', 'salem', 'tanjore', 'hyderabad', 'bangalore', 'vellore', 'pondicherry', 'nagercoil', 'mysore']
    north_region = ['gurgaon', 'noida', 'delhi /ncr', 'delhi', 'ghaziabad', 'lucknow', 'agra', 'kanpur', 'faizabad']
    west_region = ['mumbai', 'pune', 'panjim']
    east_region = ['kolkata', 'allahabad', 'cuttack', 'bhubaneshwar']
    central_region = ['belgaum', 'patna', 'chitoor', 'anantapur', 'warangal', 'ahmedabad', 'kurnool', 'vijayawada', 'agra', 'baddi', 'tuticorin', 'tirupati', 'faizabad', 'ambur', 'chandigarh', 'hissar']

    if location in south_region:
        return 'South Region'
    elif location in north_region:
        return 'North Region'
    elif location in west_region:
        return 'West Region'
    elif location in east_region:
        return 'East Region'
    elif location in central_region:
        return 'Central Region'
    else:
        return 'Other Region'

# Update the 'native_loc' column with the corresponding regions
df['native_loc'] = df['native_loc'].apply(map_to_region)

The term "routine" is generally associated with tasks or activities that are repetitive, regular, and commonly performed as part of regular procedures. In the context of job skills, labeling a skill as "routine" might imply that it involves standard, well-established procedures that are consistently applied. These skills are often fundamental and may not require specialized or advanced training.

In contrast, "skilled" typically refers to tasks or activities that require specific expertise, training, or a higher level of proficiency. Skilled tasks may involve a deeper understanding of the subject matter, specialized knowledge, or the ability to perform complex operations.

Convert date into weekdays¶

In [ ]:
from datetime import datetime

#function to check if a character is between a-z or 1-9
def is_myalnum(char):
    return (ord(char.lower()) in range(ord('a'), ord('z')+1)
            or char.isdigit())

#extracts the day, month and year from the data
def parse_string(date_str):

    date = [] #contain [day, month, year]
    val = ""
    
    counter = 0
    str_len = len(date_str)
    
    while (len(date) < 3):
        char = date_str[counter]
        #print(counter, str_len, char, is_myalnum(char))
        
        if is_myalnum(char):
            val += char
        
        elif not is_myalnum(char) and not val == "":
            date.append(val)
            val = ""

        if counter == (str_len - 1) and not val == "":
            date.append(val)
            val = ""
        
        counter += 1
    return date
    
#converts the date into a weekday
def convert_date(data):

    [day, month, year]= parse_string(data)

    year = int(year)
    day = int(day)
    if month.isdigit(): 
        date = datetime(year, int(month), day)
                        
    else:
        month = int(datetime.strptime(month, "%b").strftime("%m"))
        date = datetime(year, month, day)

    return date.strftime('%A')
        
df.weekday = df.weekday.apply(convert_date)

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Create the Decision Tree Classifier
dt_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5, random_state=123)

# Fit the model to the training data
dt_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test data
dt_predictions = dt_model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate performance
# Calculate accuracy
dt_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, dt_predictions)
print("Decision Tree Classifier Accuracy:", dt_accuracy)

# Calculate precision
dt_precision = precision_score(y_test, dt_predictions)
print("Precision:", dt_precision)

# Calculate recall
dt_recall = recall_score(y_test, dt_predictions)
print("Recall:", dt_recall)

# Generate and display a confusion matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y_test, dt_predictions), annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['Negative', 'Positive'], yticklabels=['Negative', 'Positive'])
plt.title('Confusion Matrix - Decision Tree Classifier')
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.show()
